  "text": "Physiological make-up, anthropometrics, age, fitness levels, and particular medical conditions can have an impact on one's susceptibility to cold weather injuries. Ethnicity and gender can also put people at higher risk for cold weather injuries. [CITATION_1] As the Canadian Armed Forces continues to diversify and attract more women and visible minorities including, those from warm or tropical parts of the world, there could potentially be a selection issue that impacts health risk for operations in the Arctic. The diminished ability for certain people to vasodilate the peripheral circulation is well documented in the scientific literature. [CITATION_2] We should therefore be accounting for this biological factor, and work to protect the various populations who deploy in harsh arctic conditions by providing the best clothing, methods for prevention the best medical treatment available.",
